# ============================================================================
# Auto-generated EXPLAIN snapshot for all mz_catalog_server objects.
#
# PURPOSE
#   This file captures the EXPLAIN plan of every index, materialized view,
#   and (system-schema) view that is maintained or defined on the
#   `mz_catalog_server` cluster. Changing the SQL of one builtin catalog
#   object (a view's query, an index's key, ...) can silently shift the query
#   plans -- and therefore the maintained arrangements and memory profile --
#   of *other* builtin objects. Those downstream plan changes are otherwise
#   invisible in a PR diff. This snapshot makes them visible.
#
#   A large diff in this file on a PR that did not intend to change builtin
#   catalog SQL is a signal to INVESTIGATE, not noise to blanket-rewrite.
#
# HOW TO REGENERATE
#   The list of EXPLAIN queries below is auto-generated by enumerating the
#   catalog; the expected plans are filled in by sqllogictest. Never edit the
#   region between the BEGIN/END markers by hand.
#
#   1. Refresh the *list of queries* (after adding/removing a builtin object
#      on mz_catalog_server, or a system-schema view):
#
#        bin/mzcompose --find sqllogictest run catalog-server-explain --rewrite
#
#   2. Refresh the *expected plans* (after the list is up to date, or after a
#      plan changes):
#
#        bin/sqllogictest -- --rewrite-results \
#          test/sqllogictest/catalog_server_explain.slt
#
#   The `sqllogictest` SLT run asserts (on one CI shard) that every
#   mz_catalog_server object has a matching EXPLAIN query here, so newly added
#   builtins cannot silently escape coverage, and this file is part of the
#   normal sqllogictest run so any plan change shows up as a diff.
#
#   The validator and the embedded server that fills these plans both derive
#   their system parameters from `get_default_system_parameters()`, so they
#   enable the same flag-gated builtins and coverage here is complete, not
#   conditional.
# ============================================================================

mode cockroach

# Start from a pristine server so no user objects (e.g. roles created by a
# preceding file in the same run) leak into the constant-folded plans. Several
# `information_schema` views embed the current set of role OIDs as a literal,
# which would otherwise make this snapshot depend on run order.
reset-server

# `mz_internal.mz_wallclock_global_lag` is a monotonic top-1 over a temporal
# filter; planning it folds `mz_now()` into a literal millisecond timestamp that
# changes on every run. Mask that one literal so the snapshot stays stable. The
# regex and replacement are separated by two spaces (see the `replace` directive
# in src/sqllogictest). This is the only object whose plan embeds a volatile
# value; every other `mz_now()` stays symbolic in its plan.
replace (> )\d{13}  ${1}<TIMESTAMP>

# `mz_catalog.mz_kafka_sources` folds `mz_environment_id()` into the plan as a
# literal (see the `expr: resolve mz_environment_id() to a plan-time literal`
# commit). The literal embeds a per-run UUID, so mask it so the snapshot stays
# stable across environments.
replace local-az1-[0-9a-f-]{36}-0  local-az1-<ENV_ID>

# Plan views against the cluster that actually maintains the catalog
# arrangements, so unindexed views resolve the same indexes they would in
# production.
statement ok
SET cluster = mz_catalog_server

# BEGIN AUTO-GENERATED QUERIES (regenerate with: bin/mzcompose --find sqllogictest run catalog-server-explain --rewrite)

